In this video, we'll look at collisions.

2
00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Oftentimes, when we're importing into Unreal Engine,

3
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:08.000
we'll have a checkbox available to us that asks

4
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.000
if we would like to generate missing collisions.

5
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:14.000
This will tell Unreal Engine that when we're walking around a scene,

6
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.000
especially in, for example, a third-person character template,

7
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:22.000
that we should bump into and not go through certain kinds of geometry.

8
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:24.000
As we see in the bottom right,

9
00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.000
we can also have collisions set up manually,

10
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:30.000
in this case, just affecting the columns,

11
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
which is particularly useful if we have more complex geometry

12
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.000
above the height that a character will be able to access,

13
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
and there's no reason to have collision data there.

14
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:42.000
To give your CPU a break, it's always ideal to keep your collisions

15
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
as simple as possible, but if your platform can handle it,

16
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
there are also very simple ways to make all the geometry

17
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
just match the same collision data as the geometry itself.

18
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Here's an example of modeling a custom collision box

19
00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:57.000
over in a DCC tool.

20
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
You can see that it's much simpler than the geometry inside of it,

21
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.000
but will still allow more complex collisions

22
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
than something like a simple box or sphere.

23
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:09.000
These collision meshes can import into Unreal Engine automatically

24
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.000
as long as they follow the naming convention of the prefix

25
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:18.000
ucx underscore, full mesh name, underscore number.

26
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Let's take a look at the collisions map in Content Maps,

27
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
where we'll see that we've got a simple wall

28
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.000
with a hole cut through it,

29
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
some various objects on the ground, and some columns.

30
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.000
So if we go ahead and start by looking at our Flayer collision,

31
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.000
we can see that these are already set up

32
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
in a pretty useful way that gives us a good sense

33
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.000
of how collisions should work.

34
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
So if we think our character is going to be able to hit the top of this wall,

35
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:50.000
of course, we want this tab collision,

36
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:53.000
whereas with the much taller columns,

37
00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:58.000
we probably don't need to go above the height that the player could jump or reach to,

38
00:01:58.000 --> 00:01:59.000
so this is perfectly fine.

39
00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:04.000
There's no need to get into the details of every nook and cranny of these columns.

40
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Down here, we want these, of course, to be a little bit more convex.

41
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.000
And so these are set up just enough to be able to block the player

42
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.000
in a more robust way than a simple cube or sphere would be able to.

43
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:20.000
Let's take a look at these a little bit closer.

44
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
So if I open up Cart Damaged,

45
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
and I view the collision here,

46
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
we can see that this was set up as a convex element.

47
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.000
So if we wanted to try creating something like this ourselves,

48
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:39.000
we could go and remove collision,

49
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
and then try doing this with auto-convex collision.

50
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
It'll ask us what we want the whole count and the max vertices to be.

51
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:52.000
I can hit apply, and it will give us something actually a little bit more detailed

